m","Stopham, Sussex, England":"Stopham, Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forde","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan, Dermot, Aine, Fionnuala, Liam, Nuala.","English and Irish: variant of   Ford   1 and 2. This is a very common spelling in Ireland.","Norwegian (<b>Førde</b>): habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Førde (there are eleven on the west coast), from Old Norse <i>fyrthi</i>, dative of <i>fjǫrthr</i> ‘fjord’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ford","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived near a ford (Middle English, Old English <i>ford</i>), or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, such as Ford (Durham, Herefordshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Sussex), Ford in Sefton (Lancashire), Ford in Crediton and Ford in Holcombe Rogus (both Devon), Ford in Litton and Ford in Wiveliscombe (both Somerset).","Irish: Anglicized form (quasi-translation) of various Gaelic names, for example <b>MacGiolla na Naomh</b> ‘son of <i>Gilla na Naomh</i>’ (a personal name meaning ‘servant of the saints’), <b>Mac Conshámha</b> ‘son of <i>Conshnámha</i>’ (a personal name composed of the elements <i>con</i> ‘dog’ + <i>snámh</i> ‘to swim’), in all of which the final syllable was wrongly thought to be <i>áth</i> ‘ford’, and <b>Ó Fuar(th)áin</b> (see   Foran  ).","Americanized form of French   Faure   ‘blacksmith’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":21,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":46,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":59,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":68,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":113,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Forde was born in 1269, in Stopham, Sussex, England, his father, Peter atte Forde, was 24 and his